      <!-- Content / SEO -->
      <h2>About the Bleach Filler List</h2>
      <p>Bleach, created by Tite Kubo, ran for 366 episodes from 2004 to 2012. Like many long-running Shōnen anime adapted from an ongoing manga, the anime frequently inserted filler arcs and standalone episodes to avoid overtaking the source material. Roughly 45% of the original Bleach anime is filler — one of the highest filler ratios among the "Big Three" (Naruto, Bleach, One Piece).</p>

      <h3>What counts as filler?</h3>
      <p>Filler episodes are those not adapted from the original manga. They introduce anime-original storylines, characters, and conflicts that don't affect the main canon plot. In Bleach, filler ranges from entire multi-episode arcs (like the 46-episode Bount Arc) to individual standalone episodes inserted between canon storylines. Mixed episodes contain some canon content alongside anime-original scenes.</p>

      <h3>Should you skip Bleach filler?</h3>
      <p>For first-time viewers who want the core Ichigo Kurosaki story, skipping filler is recommended. The main plot flows naturally from one canon arc to the next, and no filler arc is referenced in later canon episodes. For fans who've already seen the series or want more Bleach content, some filler arcs are worth watching — particularly the Zanpakutō Unknown Tales Arc, which features creative fights and solid animation.</p>

      <h3>Episode type breakdown</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Canon episodes (~203):</strong> Directly adapted from Tite Kubo's manga, covering the story from Ichigo gaining Shinigami powers through the Fullbring Arc.</li>
        <li><strong>Filler episodes (~163):</strong> Anime-original content including the Bount, Amagai, Zanpakutō, and Invading Army arcs plus standalone episodes.</li>
        <li><strong>TYBW:</strong> The sequel series is entirely canon, adapting the manga's final arc with no filler.</li>
      </ul>

